N2 adsorption-desorption isotherms of Ag3PO4/NP-CQDs/rGH inherited the S-type pore structure of rGH (Fig. 3
                        a). The Ag3PO4/NP-CQDs/rGH and rGH were mainly composed of mesoporous structure (pore diameter: 2–50 nm), while N, P-CQDs/Ag3PO4 and Ag3PO4 was owned the micropore structure (pore diameter: <2 nm) in Fig. 3b and Fig. S3. The surface area (131.1 m2/g), pore volume (0.38 cm3/g) and pore diameter (4.418 nm) in Ag3PO4/NP-CQDs/rGH were significantly higher than Ag3PO4 monomer, N, P-CQDs/Ag3PO4 and rGH (Table 1
                        ). The highest specific surface area and pore volume of Ag3PO4/NP-CQDs/rGH could enhance absorption capability. The rGH exhibited better adsorptive activate due to hydrophobicity and the competitive adsorption of H2O. The surface area of alone N, P-CQDs/Ag3PO4 (25.44 m2/g) was raised much better after rGH supported, which would facilitate the reaction area sites. In addition, the crystal particle reduced the accumulation of rGH for synergism each other [24].
